            <section class="summary-box">
              <h2>TL;DR</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>"Vector" is a directional term in math but an organic term in epidemiology.</li>
                <li><strong>Physics/Math:</strong> A quantity with magnitude and direction (e.g., velocity).</li>
                <li><strong>Biology:</strong> An organism that transmits a disease (e.g., mosquito).</li>
                <li><strong>CompSci:</strong> A dynamic array or data structure (e.g., std::vector).</li>
                <li><strong>Graphic Design:</strong> Scalable geometry (SVG) vs Raster (Pixels).</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="article-section">
              <h2>What does "Vector" refer to?</h2>
              <p>The Latin root meaning "carrier" allows this word to inhabit multiple disciplines. It carries force in physics, carries disease in biology, and carries data in programming. Without context, it is impossible to define.</p>
            </section>

             <section class="article-section">
              <h2>Etymology: The Carrier</h2>
              <p>The word comes from the Latin <em>vehere</em> (to carry, convey). This root is the key to understanding all modern definitions:</p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Physics:</strong> A vector "carries" an object from Point A to Point B.</li>
                <li><strong>Biology:</strong> A mosquito "carries" the pathogen to the host.</li>
                <li><strong>C++:</strong> A vector "carries" a dynamic list of variables in memory.</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

